## Part 2: Data Processing

- Clearly handle missing values with justifications:
  - GRE Score: Replace missing with median. Why is median preferred here?
  - Research: Replace missing with mode. Explain your reasoning clearly.
  - CGPA: Replace missing with mean. Justify your choice of mean here.
```{r}
clean_admission <- admission %>% mutate(`GRE Score` =replace_na(`GRE Score`, median(`GRE Score` ,na.rm=TRUE)))

clean_admission <- clean_admission %>% mutate(`Research`=replace_na(`Research`,1)) 

clean_admission <- clean_admission %>% mutate(`CGPA` =replace_na(`CGPA`, mean(`CGPA` ,na.rm=TRUE)))
```
I chose the median because GRE scores can sometimes very high or very low(outliers)
the median is the middle value, it is not effected by extreme scores, so it gives a more accurate typical score for a student when data is missing.

Research experience is either 0 or 1. You cannot have an mean of 0.55 research experience. Using the mode (the most frequent value, which is 1 in this data) is the only logical way to fill in a category.
we know that the mode is 1 because at the summery output the median research is 1, it means that at least 50% or more of the student have research experience.

The Mean (8.603) and the Median (8.61) are almost identical. This tells us that there are no significant outliers that would distort the average.
CGPA is already a calculated average of a student's grades, the Mean is the most natural to fill in missing values without changing the overall balance of the dataset.

