## Part 3: Data Visualization

Select and create **four informative plots** using **ggplot2**:

- Clearly justify why each plot was chosen and discuss the insights each provides about the Titanic dataset. One plot should specifically focus on an interaction between three or more variables. Explain the complexity and your reasoning for this choice.
```{r}
ggplot(clean_titanic, aes(Pclass, fill =factor(Survived))) + geom_bar(position="fill") + labs(title = "Survival proportion by class", x= "Passenger class", y= "Propotion", fill= "Survival")

ggplot(clean_titanic, aes(factor(Pclass), y= Age)) + geom_boxplot(alpha=0.7) + labs(title = "Age distribution by classes", x = "Class", y = "Age")

ggplot(clean_titanic, aes(Age, Fare, color=factor(Survived))) + geom_point() + scale_y_log10() + labs(title="Survival by Age and Fare", y= "Fare(Log Scale)", color="Survived")

ggplot(clean_titanic, aes(Age, fill=factor(Survived))) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5, position = "stack") + facet_grid(Sex ~ Pclass) + labs(title = "Survival Interaction: Age, Sex, and Class", x="Age", y="Passenger Count", fill="survival")
```
I chose stacked bar chart with percentage normalization (position="fill") to examine the categorical relationship between socio-economic status and survival probability.
If you were in 1st class, you had a much higher chance of surviving compared to 3rd class. It proves that money and status played a big role in who got onto the lifeboats.

With boxplot we can see the median, range and the outliears of the age in each class at the same time.
We can see that 1st-class passengers were generally older, while 3rd-class passengers were much younger. This explains why I filled missing age values based on the class, because "average age" is different for each group.

I wanted to see every single passenger as a dot on a map of Age and Ticket Price. I used a Log Scale for the price so the very expensive tickets wouldn't ruin the view of the cheaper ones.
The blue dots are mostly at the top or on the far left. This tells us that if you didn't have money, your only other "protection" was being a child.

I combined three things- Gender, Class, and Age- into one view using Facets.
I did this because looking at just one thing (like gender) doesn't tell the whole story.
We know that women and children is first but we can see that Class is also a factor.
A woman in 3rd class was much less likely to survive than a woman in 1st class. It shows that gender, age, and money all interacted together to decide a passenger's fate
